Analogy - Styling a house

Bedroom {
	drapes: blue;
	carpet: wool shag;
}

Each CSS statement has:
	Location (E.g bedroom)
	Property (Drapes, carpet)
	Style (Blue, wool shag)

location will be HTML element(s)
Property will be some style option
Style will be specific to property


Integrate w/ HTML

Option one (Lazy way | Annying to configure) 
	Put the style in the HTML code
Option Two (Better way | Easy manipulation with in CSS)
	Create a seperate file with .css Increment and use this
Allowed to combine rules together as one
Allowed to apply multiple of the same rule
ex-
h1, h2 {
	font-family: sans-serif;
	color: grey;
	border-bottom: 1px solid black;
}


CSS:<link> element

Create an external link to .css file from HTML files
- Add <link> element into <head> element

<link href="style.css" style="text/css" rel="stylesheet">

href="" | files location
style="" | specifies file as CSS (optional)
rel="" | specifies relationship


Inheritance
HTML elemets inherit style from their parent


Style the whole page
if you style the <body> | each child will follow that rule unless specified for the specific child


Want to stylize individual elements?
	or groups of elements?

add class attribute to HTML element
elect class in CSS using element.className

in the style sheet, you are stating the tag then the name then your CSS items inside curly brackets

Ex
<p class="green-p"> Text </p>
<p class="red-p"> Text </p>

p.green-p {
	color:green;
}
p.red-p {
	background-color: red
	color: green;
}

Classes are for grops of elements
- can use id attribte and hashtag (#) to style specific element

add id attribte to HTML element
select id in CSS using element#id


